text: It‚Äôs time for the money talk and it will not be an easy one. This week, EU states and institutions will start negotiating the budget of the European Union for the next 7 years (2020-2027). But with Brexit looming, many member states already said they will not fill in the gap. The situation is critical though: Europe will need more money if it is to deliver on the many challenges we are facing, including social inequality, climate change and migration. And don‚Äôt get fooled by ...the populists who like to spread lies; over 93% of the EU budget goes back to the states and the citizens (in 2017, 6.3% was used for administration). In fact, citizens would be the first beneficiaries of an increased EU budget.  The European Parliament will of course have its say. As Socialists and Democrats, we want to ensure that Europe gets the budget it needs to get the job done. It is also high time for the EU to get its own financial resources and to be less dependent on national contributions. No more rebates either; it‚Äôs time for equality and transparency between all EU states. Let the money talk begin. We stand ready See more
